<subSubSection id="C3106571FB747A40CFCB35370443FDF6" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="18" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BB536FAFB747A41CFCB3537006BF965" blockId="16.[189,334,1648,1674]" box="[189,334,1648,1674]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<heading id="D0FD8196FB747A41CFCB3537006BF965" bold="true" box="[189,334,1648,1674]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B97EEAE8FB747A41CFCB3537006BF965" bold="true" box="[189,334,1648,1674]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB536FAFB747A40CFCB35D80443FDF6" blockId="16.[189,1400,1695,2003]" lastBlockId="17.[188,1400,265,538]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="18" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
SHELL (
<figureCitation id="13312A7FFB747A41CE6035D80047F956" box="[278,354,1695,1721]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="18.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[195,1392,296,1866]" captionTargetId="figure-18@18.[189,1399,281,1873]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Fig. 7. Gulella crookesi sp. nov., holotype (NMSA P1680/T4526), length 2.44 mm, width 1.17 mm. A. Aperture view. B. Side view. C. View into aperture. D. Oblique view of base showing umbilicus. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6448773" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6448773/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Shell minute, sub-cylindrical to squat, length 
<quantity id="4CF29B1FFB747A41CCDD35D80565F956" box="[939,1088,1695,1721]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="2.6" metricValueMin="2.4" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="2.5" valueMax="2.6" valueMin="2.4">2.4–2.6 mm</quantity>
, width 
<quantity id="4CF29B1FFB747A41CBEB35D80417F956" box="[1181,1330,1695,1721]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="1.15" valueMax="1.2" valueMin="1.1">1.1–1.2 mm</quantity>
, L:W 2.0–2.2 (n = 7). Protoconch approx. 
<quantity id="4CF29B1FFB747A41CDF0358503C0F932" box="[646,741,1730,1757]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="0.9">0.9 mm</quantity>
in diameter, comprising approx. 2.5 whorls, smooth; junction between protoconch and teleoconch not distinct. Teleoconch comprising approx. 4 whorls; whorls weakly convex; smooth and glossy but with fine growth lines (
<figureCitation id="13312A7FFB747A41CC84344F0554F8CC" box="[1010,1137,1800,1827]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="18.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[195,1392,296,1866]" captionTargetId="figure-18@18.[189,1399,281,1873]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Fig. 7. Gulella crookesi sp. nov., holotype (NMSA P1680/T4526), length 2.44 mm, width 1.17 mm. A. Aperture view. B. Side view. C. View into aperture. D. Oblique view of base showing umbilicus. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6448773" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6448773/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 7A, B</figureCitation>
), surface often eroded and pitted even in live-collected shells; axial pleats on lower half of last whorl and around umbilicus (
<figureCitation id="13312A7FFB747A41CFBE34080003F886" box="[200,294,1871,1897]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="18.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[195,1392,296,1866]" captionTargetId="figure-18@18.[189,1399,281,1873]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Fig. 7. Gulella crookesi sp. nov., holotype (NMSA P1680/T4526), length 2.44 mm, width 1.17 mm. A. Aperture view. B. Side view. C. View into aperture. D. Oblique view of base showing umbilicus. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6448773" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6448773/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 7D</figureCitation>
), extending to adapical suture just prior to outer lip (
<figureCitation id="13312A7FFB747A41CCF9340802C9F886" box="[911,1004,1871,1897]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="18.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[195,1392,296,1866]" captionTargetId="figure-18@18.[189,1399,281,1873]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Fig. 7. Gulella crookesi sp. nov., holotype (NMSA P1680/T4526), length 2.44 mm, width 1.17 mm. A. Aperture view. B. Side view. C. View into aperture. D. Oblique view of base showing umbilicus. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6448773" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6448773/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 7B</figureCitation>
). Aperture narrower towards base on right hand side (in aperture view); peristome thickened and reflected; aperture markedly constricted by teeth, dentition nine-fold (
<figureCitation id="13312A7FFB747A41CD6A34D20359F840" box="[540,636,1941,1967]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="18.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[195,1392,296,1866]" captionTargetId="figure-18@18.[189,1399,281,1873]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Fig. 7. Gulella crookesi sp. nov., holotype (NMSA P1680/T4526), length 2.44 mm, width 1.17 mm. A. Aperture view. B. Side view. C. View into aperture. D. Oblique view of base showing umbilicus. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6448773" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6448773/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 7C</figureCitation>
): 1) a parietal lamella, with outer portion markedly oblique and then curving inward so that remainder runs into aperture, and with a notch in its lower margin; 2) a large triangular labral tooth, its upper margin sinuous and with a denticle near lip edge and another further into aperture; 3, 4 and 5) two deeply inset ridge-like basal teeth in close apposition plus one behind labral tooth, visible through translucent shell, 6) a low, broad rounded denticle at base of somewhat thickened columella lip, and in some specimens, an even less prominent one at top of columella lip; 7–9) a large inset tricuspid columella lamella, the upper and middle teeth large and rounded (particularly the middle one), the lower one smaller, often little more than a bump. Labral tooth corresponds with a deep pit behind outer lip (
<figureCitation id="13312A7FFB757A40CEFF329B00C2FE18" box="[393,487,476,503]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="18.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[195,1392,296,1866]" captionTargetId="figure-18@18.[189,1399,281,1873]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Fig. 7. Gulella crookesi sp. nov., holotype (NMSA P1680/T4526), length 2.44 mm, width 1.17 mm. A. Aperture view. B. Side view. C. View into aperture. D. Oblique view of base showing umbilicus. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6448773" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6448773/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 7B</figureCitation>
). Umbilicus widely open, elongate-oval, approx. 
<quantity id="4CF29B1FFB757A40CB58329B05ACFE18" box="[1070,1161,476,503]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" unit="mm" value="0.2">0.2 mm</quantity>
in length (
<figureCitation id="13312A7FFB757A40CA7C329B044CFE18" box="[1290,1385,476,503]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="18.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[195,1392,296,1866]" captionTargetId="figure-18@18.[189,1399,281,1873]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Fig. 7. Gulella crookesi sp. nov., holotype (NMSA P1680/T4526), length 2.44 mm, width 1.17 mm. A. Aperture view. B. Side view. C. View into aperture. D. Oblique view of base showing umbilicus. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6448773" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6448773/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 7D</figureCitation>
). Shell almost transparent when fresh, orange-red coloration of dried tissue of animal visible internally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3106571FB757A40CFCB3107000CFD43" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BB536FAFB757A40CFCB31070093FDB4" blockId="17.[189,438,576,603]" box="[189,438,576,603]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="B97EEAE8FB757A40CFCB31070073FDB5" bold="true" box="[189,342,576,602]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Distribution</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13312A7FFB757A40CE1031060088FDB4" box="[358,429,577,603]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[189,232,1963,1989]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,1181,1899]" captionTargetId="figure-327@6.[189,1398,1181,1899]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 2. Distribution map of Gulella kenbrowni sp. nov. (pink circles), G. fordycei sp. nov. (blue squares), G. mkombeni sp. nov. (green triangles) and G. crookesi sp. nov. (orange square). Contour at 1000 m." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6448759" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6448759/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB536FAFB757A40CFCB3137000CFD43" blockId="17.[188,1398,623,685]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Known only from Vernon Crookes Nature Reserve, in southern 
<collectingRegion id="49CEF818FB757A40CCD631280579FD66" box="[928,1116,623,649]" country="South Africa" name="KwaZulu-Natal" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">KwaZulu-Natal</collectingRegion>
; at approx. 
<quantity id="4CF29B1FFB757A40CB973128040FFD65" box="[1249,1322,623,650]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" unit="m" value="400.0">400 m</quantity>
above sea level.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3106571FB757A40CFCB319305CDFCF3" box="[189,1256,724,797]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BB536FAFB757A40CFCB31930038FD01" blockId="17.[189,285,724,750]" box="[189,285,724,750]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<heading id="D0FD8196FB757A40CFCB31930038FD01" bold="true" box="[189,285,724,750]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B97EEAE8FB757A40CFCB31930038FD01" bold="true" box="[189,285,724,750]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Habitat</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB536FAFB757A40CFCB304505CDFCF3" blockId="17.[189,1256,770,797]" box="[189,1256,770,797]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Patches of 
<collectingRegion id="49CEF818FB757A40CE48304500D3FCF3" box="[318,502,770,796]" country="South Africa" name="KwaZulu-Natal" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">KwaZulu-Natal</collectingRegion>
Scarp forest (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9B4B0BFB757A40CDEF304502A9FCF2" author="Mucina L. &amp; Lotter M. C. &amp; Tichy L. &amp; Siebert S. J. &amp; Scott-Shaw C. R." box="[665,908,770,797]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="125 - 225" refId="ref16288" refString="Mucina L., Lotter M. C., Tichy L., Siebert S. J. &amp; Scott-Shaw C. R. 2018 b. Classification of the Eastern scarp forests. In: Mucina L. (ed.) Vegetation Survey and Classification of Subtropical Forests of Southern Africa: 125 - 225. Geobotany Studies series. Springer, Cham, Switzerland. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 3 - 319 - 67831 - 3 _ 6" type="book chapter" year="2018">
Mucina 
<emphasis id="B97EEAE8FB757A40CD8A30440212FCF3" box="[764,823,770,796]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">et al.</emphasis>
2018b
</bibRefCitation>
); in leaf-litter and under logs.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3106571FB757A40CFCB3003046AFB2A" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BB536FAFB757A40CFCB3003000AFCB1" blockId="17.[189,303,836,862]" box="[189,303,836,862]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<heading id="D0FD8196FB757A40CFCB3003000AFCB1" bold="true" box="[189,303,836,862]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B97EEAE8FB757A40CFCB3003000AFCB1" bold="true" box="[189,303,836,862]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB536FAFB757A40CFCB3035050FFB8F" blockId="17.[187,1399,882,1120]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
The two closely adpressed, ridge-like basal teeth are unusual; in taxa with a basal tooth to the right of centre, it is usually low and transverse, not in-running. The tricuspid columella lamella of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4D79FB757A40CFCB30FE0058FC3C" authority="Cole &amp; Herbert, 2022" authorityName="Cole &amp; Herbert" authorityYear="2022" box="[189,381,953,979]" class="Gastropoda" family="Streptaxidae" genus="Gulella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="crookesi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B97EEAE8FB757A40CFCB30FE0058FC3C" box="[189,381,953,979]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Gulella crookesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24D5793FB757A40CEF530FE00F9FC3C" box="[387,476,953,979]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
resembles that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4D79FB757A40CDDC30FE020EFC3C" authority="Cole &amp; Herbert, 2022" authorityName="Cole &amp; Herbert" authorityYear="2022" box="[682,811,953,979]" class="Gastropoda" family="Charopidae" genus="Amatholedonta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="fordycei" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B97EEAE8FB757A40CDDC30FE020EFC3C" box="[682,811,953,979]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">G. fordycei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24D5793FB757A40CC4530FE02A9FC3C" box="[819,908,953,979]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and several species from the 
<collectingRegion id="49CEF818FB757A40CBAB30FE0453FC3C" box="[1245,1398,953,979]" country="South Africa" name="Eastern Cape" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Eastern Cape</collectingRegion>
coast, particularly 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4D79FB757A40CEE5309B0304FC19" authorityName="Cole &amp; Herbert" authorityYear="2009" box="[403,545,988,1014]" class="Gastropoda" family="Streptaxidae" genus="Gulella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="bomvana">
<emphasis id="B97EEAE8FB757A40CEE5309B0304FC19" box="[403,545,988,1014]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">G. bomvana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4D79FB757A40CD21309B03D0FC19" authority="Cole &amp; Herbert, 2022" authorityName="Cole &amp; Herbert" authorityYear="2022" box="[599,757,988,1014]" class="Gastropoda" family="Streptaxidae" genus="Gulella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="kenbrowni" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B97EEAE8FB757A40CD21309B03D0FC19" box="[599,757,988,1014]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">G. kenbrowni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24D5793FB757A40CD8A309A0273FC18" box="[764,854,989,1015]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
The latter two taxa are also smooth and glossy. The labral tooth of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4D79FB757A40CED43747030DFBF6" authority="Cole &amp; Herbert, 2022" authorityName="Cole &amp; Herbert" authorityYear="2022" box="[418,552,1023,1050]" class="Gastropoda" family="Streptaxidae" genus="Gulella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="crookesi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B97EEAE8FB757A40CED43747030DFBF6" box="[418,552,1023,1050]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">G. crookesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24D5793FB757A40CD46374703AEFBF5" box="[560,651,1024,1050]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is relatively larger than that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4D79FB757A40CC88374705A4FBF6" authority="Cole &amp; Herbert, 2022" authorityName="Cole &amp; Herbert" authorityYear="2022" box="[1022,1153,1023,1050]" class="Gastropoda" family="Charopidae" genus="Amatholedonta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="fordycei" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B97EEAE8FB757A40CC88374705A4FBF6" box="[1022,1153,1023,1050]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">G. fordycei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24D5793FB757A40CBFF374705C3FBF5" box="[1161,1254,1024,1050]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, obstructing the aperture to a larger degree and obscuring the details of the columella lamella. The labral tooth of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4D79FB757A40CFCB37010068FB8F" authorityName="Cole &amp; Herbert" authorityYear="2009" box="[189,333,1094,1120]" class="Gastropoda" family="Streptaxidae" genus="Gulella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="bomvana">
<emphasis id="B97EEAE8FB757A40CFCB37010068FB8F" box="[189,333,1094,1120]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">G. bomvana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also very large, but it extends behind the columella lamella.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB536FAFB757A40CFCB37C0046AFB2A" blockId="17.[189,1399,1159,1221]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4D79FB757A40CFCB37C0005BFB4E" authority="Cole &amp; Herbert, 2022" authorityName="Cole &amp; Herbert" authorityYear="2022" box="[189,382,1159,1185]" class="Gastropoda" family="Streptaxidae" genus="Gulella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="crookesi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B97EEAE8FB757A40CFCB37C0005BFB4E" box="[189,382,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Gulella crookesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24D5793FB757A40CEF337CF00FAFB4D" box="[389,479,1160,1186]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
also resembles the variable species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4D79FB757A40CCFD37CF0457FB4D" authority="(Melvill &amp; Ponsonby, 1895)" baseAuthorityName="Melvill &amp; Ponsonby" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[907,1394,1159,1186]" class="Gastropoda" family="Streptaxidae" genus="Gulella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="farquhari">
<emphasis id="B97EEAE8FB757A40CCFD37CF053BFB4E" box="[907,1054,1159,1186]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">G. farquhari</emphasis>
(Melvill &amp; Ponsonby, 1895)
</taxonomicName>
, but the two basal teeth and tricuspid columella lamella immediately distinguish 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4D79FB757A40CB1137EC05C9FB2B" authority="Cole &amp; Herbert, 2022" authorityName="Cole &amp; Herbert" authorityYear="2022" box="[1127,1260,1194,1221]" class="Gastropoda" family="Streptaxidae" genus="Gulella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="crookesi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B97EEAE8FB757A40CB1137EC05C9FB2B" box="[1127,1260,1194,1221]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">G. crookesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24D5793FB757A40CB8237EC046AFB2A" box="[1268,1359,1195,1221]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3106571FB757A40CFCB37AC0558F99E" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="8BB536FAFB757A40CFCB37AC0040FAEA" blockId="17.[189,357,1259,1285]" box="[189,357,1259,1285]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<heading id="D0FD8196FB757A40CFCB37AC0040FAEA" bold="true" box="[189,357,1259,1285]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B97EEAE8FB757A40CFCB37AC0040FAEA" bold="true" box="[189,357,1259,1285]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Conservation</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB536FAFB757A40CFCB365D0558F99E" blockId="17.[188,1399,1306,1649]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4D79FB757A40CFCB365D00A7FADB" authority="Cole &amp; Herbert, 2022" authorityName="Cole &amp; Herbert" authorityYear="2022" box="[189,386,1306,1332]" class="Gastropoda" family="Streptaxidae" genus="Gulella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="crookesi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B97EEAE8FB757A40CFCB365D00A7FADB" box="[189,386,1306,1332]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Gulella crookesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24D5793FB757A40CEF8365C00C9FADA" box="[398,492,1307,1333]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
has been found only at Vernon Crookes Nature Reserve, a protected area under the jurisdiction of Ezemvelo-KZN Wildlife. The south coast of 
<collectingRegion id="49CEF818FB757A40CB7F367A05E4FAB8" box="[1033,1217,1341,1367]" country="South Africa" name="KwaZulu-Natal" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">KwaZulu-Natal</collectingRegion>
and hinterland have been extensively modified by sugarcane farming and development. Vernon Crookes Nature Reserve, although small, is a very important haven for biodiversity in the region. Twenty-nine species of terrestrial Mollusca have been recorded, including 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4D79FB757A40CC6036E0042FFA2D" authority="(Watson, 1915)" baseAuthorityName="Watson" baseAuthorityYear="1915" box="[790,1290,1447,1474]" class="Gastropoda" family="Rhytididae" genus="Chlamydephorus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="dimidius">
<emphasis id="B97EEAE8FB757A40CC6036E0056EFA2E" box="[790,1099,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Chlamydephorus dimidius</emphasis>
(Watson, 1915)
</taxonomicName>
, listed as Vulnerable and several other narrow-range species. It is the 
<typeStatus id="54B18858FB757A40CC01368C028FFA0A" box="[887,938,1483,1509]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">type</typeStatus>
and only known locality of two species of microchaetid earthworm, and the major locality for a third species which has also been recorded just outside the reserve (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9B4B0BFB757A40CEDF3556031FF9C4" author="Plisko J. D." box="[425,570,1553,1579]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="249 - 300" refId="ref16438" refString="Plisko J. D. 1998. New and little-known species of Microchaetus Rapp, 1849, with a key to all species and notes on the significance of certain morphological features (Oligochaeta: Microchaetidae). Annals of the Natal Museum 39: 249 - 300." type="journal article" year="1998">Plisko 1998</bibRefCitation>
). The reserve is surrounded by sugarcane farms and rural villages, and portions of the fence are missing, enabling cattle to enter, which poses a threat to the integrity of the indigenous forest patches and the well-being of their litter-dwelling invertebrates.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
